<DD>
<P>
<CENTER>
<H3>Requirements for a Distributed Authoring and =
Versioning</H3></CENTER>
<CENTER>
<H3>Protocol for the World Wide Web</H3></CENTER>
<DL>
  <P>
  <DT>Status of this Memo
  <DD>
  <P>This memo provides information for the Internet community. It does =
not=20
  specify an Internet standard of any kind. Distribution of this memo is =

  unlimited.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>Copyright Notice
  <DD>
  <P>Copyright (C) The Internet Society (1998). All Rights Reserved.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>Abstract
  <DD>
  <P>Current World Wide Web (WWW or Web) standards provide simple =
support for=20
  applications which allow remote editing of typed data. In practice, =
the=20
  existing capabilities of the WWW have proven inadequate to support =
efficient,=20
  scalable remote editing free of overwriting conflicts. This document =
presents=20
  a list of features in the form of requirements for a Web Distributed =
Authoring=20
  and Versioning protocol which, if implemented, would improve the =
efficiency of=20
  common remote editing operations, provide a locking mechanism to =
prevent=20
  overwrite conflicts, improve link management support between non-HTML =
data=20
  types, provide a simple attribute-value metadata facility, provide for =
the=20
  creation and reading of container data types, and integrate versioning =
into=20
  the WWW.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-1>1</A> Introduction</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>This document describes functionality which, if incorporated in an=20
  extension to the existing HTTP proposed standard [HTTP], would allow =
tools for=20
  remote loading, editing and saving (publishing) of various media types =
on the=20
  WWW to interoperate with any compliant Web server. As much as =
possible, this=20
  functionality is described without suggesting a proposed =
implementation, since=20
  there are many ways to perform the functionality within the WWW =
framework. It=20
  is also=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-2>Page 2</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>possible that a single mechanism could simultaneously satisfy =
several=20
  requirements.=20
  <P>This document reflects the consensus of the WWW Distributed =
Authoring and=20
  Versioning working group (WebDAV) as to the functionality that should =
be=20
  standardized to support distributed authoring and versioning on the =
Web. As=20
  with any set of requirements, practical considerations may make it =
impossible=20
  to satisfy them all. It is the intention of the WebDAV working group =
to come=20
  as close as possible to satisfying them in the specifications that =
make up the=20
  WebDAV protocol.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-2>2</A> Rationale</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>Current Web standards contain functionality which enables the =
editing of=20
  Web content at a remote location, without direct access to the storage =
media=20
  via an operating system. This capability is exploited by several =
existing HTML=20
  distributed authoring tools, and by a growing number of mainstream=20
  applications (e.g., word processors) which allow users to write =
(publish)=20
  their work to an HTTP server. To date, experience from the HTML =
authoring=20
  tools has shown they are unable to meet their users' needs using the=20
  facilities of Web standards. The consequence of this is either =
postponed=20
  introduction of distributed authoring capability, or the addition of=20
  nonstandard extensions to the HTTP protocol or other Web standards. =
These=20
  extensions, developed in isolation, are not interoperable.=20
  <P>Other authoring applications have wanted to access document =
repositories or=20
  version control systems through Web gateways, and have been similarly=20
  frustrated. Where this access is available at all, it is through =
nonstandard=20
  extensions to HTTP or other standards that force clients to use a =
different=20
  interface for each vendor's service.=20
  <P>This document describes requirements for a set of standard =
extensions to=20
  HTTP that would allow distributed Web authoring tools to provide the=20
  functionality their users need by means of the same standard syntax =
across all=20
  compliant servers. The broad categories of functionality that need to =
be=20
  standardized are:=20
  <P>Properties <BR>Links <BR>Locking <BR>Reservations <BR>Retrieval of=20
  Unprocessed Source <BR>Partial Write <BR>Name Space Manipulation=20
  <BR>Collections=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-3>Page 3</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>Versioning <BR>Variants <BR>Security <BR>Internationalization=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-3>3</A> Terminology</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>Where there is overlap, usage is intended to be consistent with =
that in the=20
  HTTP 1.1 specification [HTTP].=20
  <P>Client <BR>A program which issues HTTP requests and accepts =
responses.=20
  <P>Collection <BR>A collection is a resource that contains other =
resources,=20
  either directly or by reference.=20
  <P>Distributed Authoring Tool <BR>A program which can retrieve a =
source entity=20
  via HTTP, allow editing of this entity, and then save/publish this =
entity to a=20
  server using HTTP.=20
  <P>Entity <BR>The information transferred in a request or response.=20
  <P>Hierarchical Collection <BR>A hierarchical organization of =
resources. A=20
  hierarchical collection is a resource that contains other resources, =
including=20
  collections, either directly or by reference.=20
  <P>Link <BR>A typed connection between two or more resources.=20
  <P>Lock <BR>A mechanism for preventing anyone other than the owner of =
the lock=20
  from accessing a resource.=20
  <P>Member of Version Graph <BR>A resource that is a node in a version =
graph,=20
  and so is derived from the resources that precede it in the graph, and =
is the=20
  basis of those that succeed it.=20
  <P>Property <BR>Named descriptive information about a resource.=20
  <P>Reservation <BR>A declaration that one intends to edit a resource.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-4>Page 4</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>Resource <BR>A network data object or service that can be =
identified by a=20
  URI.=20
  <P>Server <BR>A program which receives and responds to HTTP requests.=20
  <P>User Agent <BR>The client that initiates a request.=20
  <P>Variant <BR>A representation of a resource. A resource may have one =
or more=20
  representations associated with it at any given time.=20
  <P>Version Graph <BR>A directed acyclic graph with resources as its =
nodes,=20
  where each node is derived from its predecessor(s).=20
  <P>Write Lock <BR>A lock that prevents anyone except its owner from =
modifying=20
  the resource it applies to.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-4>4</A> General Principles</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>This section describes a set of general principles that the WebDAV=20
  extensions should follow. These principles cut across categories of=20
  functionality.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-4.1>4.1</A> User Agent =
Interoperability</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>All WebDAV clients should be able to work with any WebDAV-compliant =
HTTP=20
  server. It is acceptable for some client/server combinations to =
provide=20
  special features that are not universally available, but the protocol =
should=20
  be sufficient that a basic level of functionality will be universal.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-4.2>4.2</A> Client Simplicity</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The WebDAV extensions should be designed to allow client=20
  <BR>implementations to be simple.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-5>Page 5</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-4.3>4.3</A> Legacy Client Support</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>It should be possible to implement a WebDAV-compliant server in =
such a way=20
  that it can interoperate with non-WebDAV clients. Such a server would =
be able=20
  to understand any valid HTTP 1.1 request from an ordinary Web client =
without=20
  WebDAV extensions, and to provide a valid HTTP 1.1 response that does =
not=20
  require the client to understand the extensions.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-4.4>4.4</A> Data Format =
Compatibility</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>WebDAV-compliant servers should be able to work with existing =
resources and=20
  URIs [URL]. Special additional information should not become a =
mandatory part=20
  of document formats.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-4.5>4.5</A> Replicated, Distributed =
Systems</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>Distribution and replication are at the heart of the Internet. All =
WebDAV=20
  extensions should be designed to allow for distribution and =
replication.=20
  Version trees should be able to be split across multiple servers. =
Collections=20
  may have members on different servers. Any resource may be cached or=20
  replicated for mobile computing or other reasons. Consequently, the =
WebDAV=20
  extensions must be able to operate in a distributed, replicated =
environment.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-4.6>4.6</A> Parsimony in Client-Server=20
  Interactions</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The WebDAV extensions should keep to a minimum the number of =
interactions=20
  between the client and the server needed to perform common functions. =
For=20
  example, publishing a document to the Web will often mean publishing =
content=20
  together with related properties. A client may often need to find out =
what=20
  version graph a particular resource belongs to, or to find out which =
resource=20
  in a version graph is the published one. The extensions should make it =

  possible to do these things efficiently.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-4.7>4.7</A> Changes to HTTP</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>WebDAV adds a number of new types of objects to the Web: =
properties,=20
  collections, version graphs, etc. Existing HTTP methods such as DELETE =
and PUT=20
  will have to operate in well-defined ways in this expanded =
environment. WebDAV=20
  should explicitly address not only new methods, headers, and MIME =
types, but=20
  also any required changes to the existing HTTP methods and headers.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-6>Page 6</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-4.8>4.8</A> Alternate Transport =
Mechanisms</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>It may be desirable to transport WebDAV requests and responses by =
other=20
  mechanisms, particularly EMail, in addition to HTTP. The WebDAV =
protocol=20
  specification should not preclude a future body from developing an=20
  interoperability specification for disconnected operation via EMail.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5>5</A> Requirements</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>In the requirement descriptions below, the requirement will be =
stated,=20
  followed by its rationale.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.1>5.1</A> Properties</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.1.1>5.1.1</A> Functional =
Requirements</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>It must be possible to create, modify, read and delete arbitrary =
properties=20
  on resources of any media type.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.1.2>5.1.2</A> Rationale</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>Properties describe resources of any media type. They may include=20
  bibliographic information such as author, title, publisher, and =
subject,=20
  constraints on usage, PICS ratings, etc. These properties have many =
uses, such=20
  as supporting searches on property values, enforcing copyrights, and =
the=20
  creation of catalog entries as placeholders for objects which are not=20
  available in electronic form, or which will be available later.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.2>5.2</A> Links</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.2.1>5.2.1</A> Functional =
Requirements</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>It must be possible to create, modify, read and delete typed links =
between=20
  resources of any media type.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.2.2>5.2.2</A> Rationale</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>One type of link between resources is the hypertext link, which is=20
  browsable using a hypertext style point-and-click user interface. =
Links,=20
  whether they are browsable hypertext links, or simply a means of =
capturing a=20
  relationship between resources, have many purposes. Links can support=20
  pushbutton printing of a multi-resource document in a prescribed =
order,=20
  jumping to the access control page for a resource, and quick browsing =
of=20
  related information, such as a table=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-7>Page 7</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>of contents, an index, a glossary, a bibliographic record, help =
pages, etc.=20
  While link support is provided by the HTML "LINK" element, this is =
limited=20
  only to HTML resources [HTML]. Similar support is needed for bitmap =
image=20
  types, and other non-HTML media types.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.3>5.3</A> Locking</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.3.1>5.3.1</A> General Principles</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.3.1.1>5.3.1.1</A> Independence of locks. =
It must be=20
  possible to lock a</STRONG>
  <DD>resource without performing an additional retrieval of the =
resource, and=20
  without committing to editing the resource.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.3.1.2>5.3.1.2</A> Multi-Resource Locking. =
It must be=20
  possible to take out a</STRONG>
  <DD>lock on multiple resources residing on the same server in a single =
action,=20
  and this locking operation must be atomic across these resources.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.3.2>5.3.2</A> Functional =
Requirements</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.3.2.1>5.3.2.1</A> Write Locks. It must be =
possible=20
  to restrict modification of</STRONG>
  <DD>a resource to a specific person.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.3.2.2>5.3.2.2</A> Lock Query. It must be =
possible to=20
  find out whether a given</STRONG>
  <DD>resource has any active locks, and if so, who holds those locks.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.3.2.3>5.3.2.3</A> Unlock. It must be =
possible to=20
  remove a lock.</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.3.3>5.3.3</A> Rationale</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>At present, the Web provides limited support for preventing two or =
more=20
  people from overwriting each other's modifications when they save to a =
given=20
  URI. Furthermore, there is no way to discover whether someone else is=20
  currently making modifications to a resource. This is known as the =
"lost=20
  update problem," or the "overwrite problem." Since there can be =
significant=20
  cost associated with discovering and repairing lost modifications, =
preventing=20
  this problem is crucial for supporting distributed authoring. A write =
lock=20
  ensures that only one person may modify a resource, preventing =
overwrites.=20
  Furthermore, locking support is a key component of many versioning =
schemes, a=20
  desirable capability for distributed authoring.=20
  <P>An author may wish to lock an entire web of resources even though =
he is=20
  editing just a single resource, to keep the other resources from =
changing. In=20
  this way, an author can ensure that if a local hypertext web is =
consistent in=20
  his distributed authoring tool, it will then be=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-8>Page 8</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>consistent when he writes it to the server. Because of this, it =
should be=20
  possible to take out a lock without also causing transmission of the =
contents=20
  of a resource.=20
  <P>It is often necessary to guarantee that a lock or unlock operation =
occurs=20
  at the same time across multiple resources, a feature which is =
supported by=20
  the multiple-resource locking requirement. This is useful for =
preventing a=20
  collision between two people trying to establish locks on the same set =
of=20
  resources, since with multi- resource locking, one of the two people =
will get=20
  a lock. If this same multiple-resource locking scenario was repeated =
by using=20
  atomic lock operations iterated across the resources, the result would =
be a=20
  splitting of the locks between the two people, based on resource =
ordering and=20
  race conditions.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.4>5.4</A> Reservations</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.4.1>5.4.1</A> Functional =
Requirements</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.4.1.1>5.4.1.1</A> Reserve. It must be =
possible for a=20
  principal to register</STRONG>
  <DD>with the server an intent to edit a given resource, so that other=20
  principals can discover who intends to edit the resource.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.4.1.2>5.4.1.2</A> Reservation Query. It =
must be=20
  possible to find out whether a</STRONG>
  <DD>given resource has any active reservations, and if so, who =
currently holds=20
  reservations.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.4.1.3>5.4.1.3</A> Release Reservation. It =
must be=20
  possible to release the</STRONG>
  <DD>reservation.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.4.2>5.4.2</A> Rationale</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>Experience from configuration management systems has shown that =
people need=20
  to know when they are about to enter a parallel editing situation. =
Once=20
  notified, they either decide not to edit in parallel with the other =
authors,=20
  or they use out-of-band communication (face- to-face, telephone, etc.) =
to=20
  coordinate their editing to minimize the difficulty of merging their =
results.=20
  Reservations are separate from locking, since a write lock does not=20
  necessarily imply a resource will be edited, and a reservation does =
not carry=20
  with it any access restrictions. This capability supports versioning, =
since a=20
  check-out typically involves taking out a write lock, making a =
reservation,=20
  and getting the resource to be edited.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-9>Page 9</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.5>5.5</A> Retrieval of Unprocessed Source =
for=20
  Editing</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.5.1>5.5.1</A> Functional =
Requirement</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The source of any given resource must be retrievable by any =
principal with=20
  authorization to edit the resource.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.5.2>5.5.2</A> Rationale</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>There are many cases where the source stored on a server does not=20
  correspond to the actual entity transmitted in response to an HTTP =
GET.=20
  Current known cases are server side include directives, and Standard=20
  Generalized Markup Language (SGML) source which is converted on the =
fly to=20
  HyperText Markup Language (HTML) [HTML] output entities. There are =
many=20
  possible cases, such as automatic conversion of bitmap images into =
several=20
  variant bitmap media types (e.g. GIF, JPEG), and automatic conversion =
of an=20
  application's native media type into HTML. As an example of this last =
case, a=20
  word processor could store its native media type on a server which=20
  automatically converts it to HTML. A GET of this resource would =
retrieve the=20
  HTML. Retrieving the source would retrieve the word processor native =
format.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.6>5.6</A> Partial Write.</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.6.1>5.6.1</A> Functional =
Requirement</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>After editing a resource, it must be possible to write only the =
changes to=20
  the resource, rather than retransmitting the entire resource.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.6.2>5.6.2</A> Rationale</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>During distributed editing which occurs over wide geographic =
separations=20
  and/or over low bandwidth connections, it is extremely inefficient and =

  frustrating to rewrite a large resource after minor changes, such as a =

  one-character spelling correction. Support is needed for transmitting =
"insert"=20
  (e.g., add this sentence in the middle of a document) and "delete" =
(e.g.=20
  remove this paragraph from the middle of a document) style updates. =
Support=20
  for partial resource updates will make small edits more efficient, and =
allow=20
  distributed authoring tools to scale up for editing large documents.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-10>Page 10</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.7>5.7</A> Name Space Manipulation</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.7.1>5.7.1</A> Copy</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.7.1.1>5.7.1.1</A> Functional =
Requirements</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>It must be possible to duplicate a resource without a client =
loading, then=20
  resaving the resource. After the copy operation, a modification to =
either=20
  resource must not cause a modification to the other.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.7.1.2>5.7.1.2</A> Rationale</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>There are many reasons why a resource might need to be duplicated, =
such as=20
  changing ownership, preparing for major modifications, or making a =
backup. Due=20
  to network costs associated with loading and saving a resource, it is =
far=20
  preferable to have a server perform a resource copy than a client.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.7.2>5.7.2</A> Move/Rename</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.7.2.1>5.7.2.1</A> Functional =
Requirements</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>It must be possible to change the location of a resource without a =
client=20
  loading, then resaving the resource under a different name. After the =
move=20
  operation, it must no longer be possible to access the resource at its =

  original location.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.7.2.2>5.7.2.2</A> Rationale</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>It is often necessary to change the name of a resource, for example =
due to=20
  adoption of a new naming convention, or if a typing error was made =
entering=20
  the name originally. Due to network costs, it is undesirable to =
perform this=20
  operation by loading, then resaving the resource, followed by a delete =
of the=20
  old resource. Similarly, a single rename operation is more efficient =
than a=20
  copy followed by a delete operation. Note that moving a resource is =
considered=20
  the same function as renaming a resource.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.8>5.8</A> Collections</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>A collection is a resource that is a container for other resources, =

  including other collections. A resource may belong to a collection =
either=20
  directly or by reference. If a resource belongs to a collection =
directly, name=20
  space operations like copy, move, and delete applied to the collection =
also=20
  apply to the resource. If a resource belongs to a collection by =
reference,=20
  name space operations applied to the collection affect only the =
reference, not=20
  the resource itself.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-11>Page 11</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.8.1>5.8.1</A> Functional =
Requirements</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.8.1.1>5.8.1.1</A> List Collection. A =
listing of all=20
  resources in a specific</STRONG>
  <DD>collection must be accessible.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.8.1.2>5.8.1.2</A> Make Collection. It must =
be=20
  possible to create a new</STRONG>
  <DD>collection.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.8.1.3>5.8.1.3</A> Add to Collection. It =
must be=20
  possible to add a resource to</STRONG>
  <DD>a collection directly or by reference.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.8.1.4>5.8.1.4</A> Remove from Collection. =
It must be=20
  possible to remove a</STRONG>
  <DD>resource from a collection.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.8.2>5.8.2</A> Rationale</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>In [URL] it states that, "some URL schemes (such as the ftp, http, =
and file=20
  schemes) contain names that can be considered hierarchical." =
Especially for=20
  HTTP servers which directly map all or part of their URL name space =
into a=20
  filesystem, it is very useful to get a listing of all resources =
located at a=20
  particular hierarchy level. This functionality supports "Save As..." =
dialog=20
  boxes, which provide a listing of the entities at a current hierarchy =
level,=20
  and allow navigation through the hierarchy. It also supports the =
creation of=20
  graphical visualizations (typically as a network) of the hypertext =
structure=20
  among the entities at a hierarchy level, or set of levels. It also =
supports a=20
  tree visualization of the entities and their hierarchy levels.=20
  <P>In addition, document management systems may want to make their =
documents=20
  accessible through the Web. They typically allow the organization of =
documents=20
  into collections, and so also want their users to be able to view the=20
  collection hierarchy through the Web.=20
  <P>There are many instances where there is not a strong correlation =
between a=20
  URL hierarchy level and the notion of a collection. One example is a =
server in=20
  which the URL hierarchy level maps to a computational process which =
performs=20
  some resolution on the name. In this case, the contents of the URL =
hierarchy=20
  level can vary depending on the input to the computation, and the =
number of=20
  resources accessible via the computation can be very large. It does =
not make=20
  sense to implement a directory feature for such a name space. However, =
the=20
  utility of listing the contents of those URL hierarchy levels which do =

  correspond to collections, such as the large number of HTTP servers =
which map=20
  their name space to a filesystem, argue for the inclusion of this =
capability,=20
  despite not being meaningful in all=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-12>Page 12</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>cases. If listing the contents of a URL hierarchy level does not =
makes=20
  sense for a particular URL, then a "405 Method Not Allowed" status =
code could=20
  be issued.=20
  <P>The ability to create collections to hold related resources =
supports=20
  management of a name space by packaging its members into small, =
related=20
  clusters. The utility of this capability is demonstrated by the broad=20
  implementation of directories in recent operating systems. The ability =
to=20
  create a collection also supports the creation of "Save As..." dialog =
boxes=20
  with "New Level/Folder/Directory" capability, common in many =
applications.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.9>5.9</A> Versioning</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.9.1>5.9.1</A> Background and General=20
  Principles</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.9.1.1>5.9.1.1</A> Stability of versions. =
Most=20
  versioning systems are intended</STRONG>
  <DD>to provide an accurate record of the history of evolution of a =
document.=20
  This accuracy is ensured by the fact that a version eventually becomes =

  "frozen" and immutable. Once a version is frozen, further changes will =
create=20
  new versions rather than modifying the original. In order for caching =
and=20
  persistent references to be properly maintained, a client must be able =
to=20
  determine that a version has been frozen. Any successful attempt to =
retrieve a=20
  frozen version of a resource will always retrieve exactly the same =
content, or=20
  return an error if that version (or the resource itself) is no longer=20
  available.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.9.1.2>5.9.1.2</A> Operations for Creating =
New=20
  Versions. Version management</STRONG>
  <DD>systems vary greatly in the operations they require, the order of =
the=20
  operations, and how they are combined into atomic functions. In the =
most=20
  complete cases, the logical operations involved are:=20
  <P>
  <UL>
    <LI>Reserve existing version </LI></UL>
  <UL>
    <LI>Lock existing version </LI></UL>
  <UL>
    <LI>Retrieve existing version </LI></UL>
  <UL>
    <LI>Request or suggest identifier for new version </LI></UL>
  <UL>
    <LI>Write new version </LI></UL>
  <UL>
    <LI>Release lock </LI></UL>
  <UL>
    <LI>Release reservation </LI></UL>
  <P>With the exception of requesting a new version identifier, all of =
these=20
  operations have applications outside of versioning and are either =
already part=20
  of HTTP or are discussed in earlier sections of these requirements. =
Typically,=20
  versioning systems combine reservation, locking, and retrieval -- or =
some=20
  subset of these -- into an atomic checkout function. They combine =
writing,=20
  releasing=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-13>Page 13</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>the lock, and releasing the reservation -- or some subset of these =
-- into=20
  an atomic checkin function. The new version identifier may be assigned =
either=20
  at checkout or at checkin.=20
  <P>The WebDAV extensions must find some balance between allowing =
versioning=20
  servers to adopt whatever policies they wish with regard to these =
operations=20
  and enforcing enough uniformity to keep client implementations simple. =

  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.9.1.3>5.9.1.3</A> The Versioning Model. =
Each version=20
  typically stands in a</STRONG>
  <DD>"derived from" relationship to its predecessor(s). It is possible =
to=20
  derive several different versions from a single version (branching), =
and to=20
  derive a single version from several versions (merging). Consequently, =
the=20
  collection of related versions forms a directed acyclic graph. In the=20
  following discussion, this graph will be called a "version graph". =
Each node=20
  of this graph is a "version" or "member of the version graph". The =
arcs of the=20
  graph capture the "derived from" relationships.=20
  <P>It is also possible for a single resource to participate in =
multiple=20
  version graphs.=20
  <P>The WebDAV extensions should support this versioning model, though=20
  particular servers may restrict it in various ways.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.9.1.4>5.9.1.4</A> Versioning Policies. =
Many writers,=20
  including Feiler [CM] and</STRONG>
  <DD>Haake and Hicks [VSE], have discussed the notion of versioning =
styles=20
  (referred to here as versioning policies, to reflect the nature of=20
  client/server interaction) as one way to think about the different =
policies=20
  that versioning systems implement. Versioning policies include =
decisions on=20
  the shape of version histories (linear or branched), the granularity =
of change=20
  tracking, locking requirements made by a server, etc. The protocol =
should=20
  clearly identify the policies that it dictates and the policies that =
are left=20
  up to versioning system implementors or administrators.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.9.1.5>5.9.1.5</A> It is possible to =
version=20
  resources of any media type.</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.9.2>5.9.2</A> Functional =
Requirements</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.9.2.1>5.9.2.1</A> Referring to a version =
graph.=20
  There must be a way to refer</STRONG>
  <DD>to a version graph as a whole.=20
  <P>Some queries and operations apply, not to any one member of a =
version=20
  graph, but to the version graph as a whole. For example, a client may =
request=20
  that an entire graph be moved, or may ask for a version history. In =
these=20
  cases, a way to refer to the whole version graph is required.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-14>Page 14</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.9.2.2>5.9.2.2</A> Referring to a specific =
member of=20
  a version graph. There</STRONG>
  <DD>must be a way to refer to each member of a version graph. This =
means that=20
  each member of the graph is itself a resource.=20
  <P>Each member of a version graph must be a resource if it is to be =
possible=20
  for a hypertext link to refer to specific version of a page, or for a =
client=20
  to request a specific version of a document for editing.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.9.2.3>5.9.2.3</A> A client must be able to =
determine=20
  whether a resource is a</STRONG>
  <DD>version graph, or whether a resource is itself a member of a =
version=20
  graph.=20
  <P>A resource may be a simple, non-versioned resource, or it may be a =
version=20
  graph, or it may be a member of a version graph. A client needs to be =
able to=20
  tell which sort of resource it is accessing.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.9.2.4>5.9.2.4</A> There must be a way to =
refer to a=20
  server-defined default</STRONG>
  <DD>member of a version graph.=20
  <P>The server should return a default version of a resource for =
requests that=20
  ask for the default version, as well as for requests where no specific =
version=20
  information is provided. This is one of the simplest ways to guarantee =

  non-versioning client compatibility. This does not rule out the =
possibility of=20
  a server returning an error when no sensible default exists.=20
  <P>It may also be desirable to be able to refer to other special =
members of a=20
  version graph. For example, there may be a current version for editing =
that is=20
  different from the default version. For a graph with several branches, =
it may=20
  be useful to be able to request the tip version of any branch.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.9.2.5>5.9.2.5</A> It must be possible, =
given a=20
  reference to a member of a</STRONG>
  <DD>version graph, to find out which version graph(s) that resource =
belongs=20
  to.=20
  <P>This makes it possible to understand the versioning context of the=20
  resource. It makes it possible to retrieve a version history for the =
graphs to=20
  which it belongs, and to browse the version graph. It also supports =
some=20
  comparison operations: It makes it possible to determine whether two=20
  references designate members of the same version graph.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.9.2.6>5.9.2.6</A> Navigation of a version =
graph.=20
  Given a reference to a</STRONG>
  <DD>member of a version graph, it must be possible to discover and =
access the=20
  following related members of the version graph.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-15>Page 15</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>
  <UL>
    <LI>root member of the graph </LI></UL>
  <UL>
    <LI>predecessor member(s) </LI></UL>
  <UL>
    <LI>successor member(s) </LI></UL>
  <UL>
    <LI>default member of the graph </LI></UL>
  <P>It must be possible in some way for a versioning client to access =
versions=20
  related to a resource currently being examined.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.9.2.7>5.9.2.7</A> Version Topology. There =
must be a=20
  way to retrieve the</STRONG>
  <DD>complete version topology for a version graph, including =
information about=20
  all members of the version graph. The format for this information must =
be=20
  standardized so that the basic information can be used by all clients. =
Other=20
  specialized formats should be <BR>accommodated, for servers and =
clients that=20
  require information that cannot be included in the standard topology.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.9.2.8>5.9.2.8</A> A client must be able to =
propose a=20
  version identifier to be</STRONG>
  <DD>used for a new member of a version graph. The server may refuse to =
use the=20
  client's suggested version identifier. The server should tell the =
client what=20
  version identifier it has assigned to the new member of the version =
graph.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.9.2.9>5.9.2.9</A> A version identifier =
must be=20
  unique across a version graph.</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.9.2.10>5.9.2.10</A> A client must be able =
to supply=20
  version-specific properties</STRONG>
  <DD>to be associated with a new member of a version graph. (See =
Section 5.1=20
  "Properties" above.) At a minimum, it must be possible to associate =
comments=20
  with the new member, explaining what changes were made.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.9.2.11>5.9.2.11</A> A client must be able =
to query=20
  the server for information</STRONG>
  <DD>about a version tree, including which versions are locked, which =
are=20
  reserved for editing, and by whom (Session Tracking).=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.9.3>5.9.3</A> Rationale</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>Versioning in the context of the world-wide web offers a variety of =

  benefits:=20
  <P>It provides infrastructure for efficient and controlled management =
of large=20
  evolving web sites. Modern configuration management systems are built =
on some=20
  form of repository that can track the revision history of individual=20
  resources, and provide the higher-level tools to manage those saved =
versions.=20
  Basic versioning capabilities are required to support such systems.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-16>Page 16</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>It allows parallel development and update of single resources. =
Since=20
  versioning systems register change by creating new objects, they =
enable=20
  simultaneous write access by allowing the creation of variant =
versions. Many=20
  also provide merge support to ease the reverse operation.=20
  <P>It provides a framework for coordinating changes to resources. =
While=20
  specifics vary, most systems provide some method of controlling or =
tracking=20
  access to enable collaborative resource development.=20
  <P>It allows browsing through past and alternative versions of a =
resource.=20
  Frequently the modification and authorship history of a resource is =
critical=20
  information in itself.=20
  <P>It provides stable names that can support externally stored links =
for=20
  annotation and link-server support. Both annotation and link servers=20
  frequently need to store stable references to portions of resources =
that are=20
  not under their direct control. By providing stable states of =
resources,=20
  version control systems allow not only stable pointers into those =
resources,=20
  but also well-defined methods to determine the relationships of those =
states=20
  of a resource.=20
  <P>It allows explicit semantic representation of single resources with =

  multiple states. A versioning system directly represents the fact that =
a=20
  resource has an explicit history, and a persistent identity across the =
various=20
  states it has had during the course of that history.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.10>5.10</A> Variants</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>Detailed requirements for variants will be developed in a separate=20
  document.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.10.1>5.10.1</A> Functional =
Requirements</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>It must be possible to send variants to the server, describing the=20
  relationships between the variants and their parent resource. In =
addition, it=20
  must be possible to write and retrieve variants of property labels, =
property=20
  descriptions, and property values.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.10.2>5.10.2</A> Rationale</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>The HTTP working group is addressing problems of content =
negotiation and=20
  retrieval of variants of a resource. To extend this work to an =
authoring=20
  environment, WEBDAV must standardize mechanisms for authors to use =
when=20
  submitting variants to a server. Authors need to be able to provide =
variants=20
  in different file or document formats, for different uses. They need =
to=20
  provide variants optimized for different=20
  <P></P>
  <DT>
  <HR>

  <DD>
  <DT><EM><A name=3Dpage-17>Page 17</A></EM>
  <DD>
  <P>clients and for different output devices. They need to be able to =
provide=20
  variants in different languages in the international environment of =
the Web.=20
  In support of internationalization requirements (See 5.12 below), =
variants=20
  need to be supported not just for the content of resources, but for =
any=20
  information intended for human use, such as property values, labels, =
and=20
  descriptions.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.11>5.11</A> Security</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.11.1>5.11.1</A> Authentication. The WebDAV =

  specification should state how the</STRONG>
  <DD>WebDAV extensions interoperate with existing authentication =
schemes, and=20
  should make recommendations for using those schemes.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.11.2>5.11.2</A> Access Control. Access =
control=20
  requirements are specified in</STRONG>
  <DD>a separate access control work in progress [AC].=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.11.3>5.11.3</A> Interoperability with =
Security=20
  Protocols. The WebDAV</STRONG>
  <DD>specification must provide a minimal list of security protocols =
which any=20
  compliant server / client must support. These protocols should insure =
the=20
  authenticity of messages and the privacy and integrity of messages in =
transit.=20

  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.12>5.12</A> Internationalization</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.12.1>5.12.1</A> Character Sets and=20
Languages</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>Since Web distributed authoring occurs in a multi-lingual =
environment,=20
  information intended for user comprehension must conform to the IETF =
Character=20
  Set Policy [CHAR]. This policy addresses character sets and encodings, =
and=20
  language tagging.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-5.12.2>5.12.2</A> Rationale</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>In the international environment of the Internet, it is important =
to insure=20
  that any information intended for user comprehension can be displayed =
in a=20
  writing system and language agreeable to both the client and the =
server. The=20
  information encompassed by this requirement includes not only the =
content of=20
  resources, but also such things as display names and descriptions of=20
  properties, property values, and status messages.=20
  <P></P>
  <DT><STRONG><A name=3Dsec-6>6</A> Acknowledgements</STRONG>
  <DD>
  <P>Our understanding of these issues has emerged as the result of much =

  thoughtful discussion, email, and assistance by many people, who =
deserve=20
  recognition for their effort.=20
  <P></P>
